# 9. Why This Works

There are three separate things to justify here: why sorting ascending is the right order, why the answer can never exceed `n`, and why the bucket-counting recurrence gives the same answer as the sorted greedy walk.

### 9.1 Why ascending sorted order is optimal (exchange argument)

Suppose two adjacent elements in some arrangement are out of order — a larger value sits immediately before a smaller one. Swap them. The smaller value can never benefit from being later (it's bounded above by its own size no matter where it sits), so moving it earlier costs nothing. The larger value, now placed later, only gets a *higher* ceiling to work with (`prev` has had more steps to climb by the time it's reached), so it can only do as well or better. Repeating this swap on every out-of-order pair sorts the array ascending without ever making the result worse — so ascending order is at least as good as any other order, which makes it optimal.

### 9.2 Why the answer can never exceed `n`

The array must start at exactly `1`, and each step can climb by **at most `+1`**. With `n` positions total, the largest value reachable at the very last position is `1 + (n - 1) = n`. No arrangement, no matter how large the original numbers are, can push any element past this ceiling — it's a structural limit, not a value limit. That's why capping every value at `n` before bucketing loses no information: anything bigger than `n` was already going to be clamped down to at most `n` anyway.

### 9.3 Why the counting recurrence matches the sorted greedy walk

Sort the array and group equal values together (sorting naturally does this). Suppose, just before processing a group of `c` identical values capped at `v`, the running value is `prev = p`. Processing the group one element at a time gives:

```text
p → min(p+1, v) → min(p+2, v) → ... → min(p+c, v)
```

Each step either advances `prev` by exactly `1`, or — once `prev` reaches `v` — simply stays at `v`. Either way, the result after the whole group is exactly `min(p + c, v)`. That is precisely the bucket recurrence `prev = min(prev + count[num], num)` — so processing a bucket all at once gives the identical result to processing its elements one at a time in the sorted walk. The bucket `1` step is the one exception, and it's justified separately by the "position 1 is always free" argument in Section 7, since it doesn't depend on how many elements actually equal `1`.

